SYMPTOM_TEXT: Symptoms & time course 03/31/21:  Within 2-3 min after taking the Covid-19 Pfizer shot in my left upper arm, my entire arm became nearly 80% immobilized ( I felt that I was going to lose my arm movement completely but it came back). In about 5 min time, I felt a strong stomach disturbance (something like stomach diarrhea) briefly for a few seconds, and then my heart rate increased suddenly a lot and I felt a strong gush of heat coming out of my face and upper half of the body, and then I started to feel unwell. I also felt moderate pressure in my ears and the head wasn't feeling well either. My hands and fingers were trembling a lot. The paramedics checked my vitals, I think the blood pressure was around 117/62 and  pulse was around 85. After another 5 minutes or so, I started to feel better.   For the next 2-3 hours post-vaccination, I had felt mild symptoms of headache, nausea, and sensation of cough in the throat. Few times I also felt mild sensations of chest discomfort and that I may develop some difficulty in breathing or shortness of breath, and once I also felt a mild sensation of throat moving up and down (no throat closure), and none of these symptoms had developed to that of a higher intensity such that someone else could see them happening. About 5 hours post-vaccination (i.e. around 8:30 pm) I felt that I have a reaction going on in the body which continued for an hour. About 6 hours post-vaccination (i.e. around 9:30 pm), I felt that the reaction that was occurring in the body had ended with the skin on both of my arms becoming red in color and the skin texture was looking like that of a burnt skin (I did not take a picture of the arm with skin redness). The whole-left-arm had swollen relatively more than the whole-right-arm and I also noted mild swelling in the left arm wrist and palm. Also, a large part of the muscle just above the elbow on the left arm had swollen a lot (appearing like a bump) with muscle stiffness, and this muscle bump was mildly painful if you apply pressure on to it. There were also some mildly painful nodules in the upper left arm and the arm muscles generally appeared to be hardened. The veins & some arteries also appeared more prominent in the left arm compared to the right arm. I had noted that the swelling and redness in both the arms had started to decrease after 30 min of appearing and got reduced a lot more after about 2 hours (i.e. 11:30 pm). There was also a very mild facial swelling at night and I had felt feverish for about 25 min or so.   04/01/21 Next day early morning (i.e. 6 am) I noted abdominal or stomach bloating of higher magnitude, and I wasn't feeling very well with some mild sensations of throat moving up and down and a feeling that I may develop shortness of breath but these symptoms did not develop in higher intensity and began to subside after about an hour. As the day progressed, I started to feel better and by afternoon all of the symptoms were better except that the swelling and a hive (or muscle bump) on the left arm were still present. I also had moderate soreness around the site of injection in the upper left arm.  04/02/21 Next day morning the swelling and hive (or muscle bump) in the upper left arm were getting better but had not completely gone. By the end of the day the arm swelling had mostly subsided and the large muscle bump in the upper arm had reduced in size but still present with a mild pain. The left upper arm soreness around the site of injection had reduced.  04/03/21 & 04/04/21 The hive or (muscle bump) in the upper left arm was highly reduced in size but still present with a mild pain on applying pressure.  04/05/21 I felt some minor chest discomfort and minor pain repeatedly for a few seconds during the afternoon hours while at work. These symptoms subsided by evening hours.  04/06/21 I felt a mild chest congestion with a little bit of phlem in the chest at night which then got better after an hour or so.  04/14/21 I noted a rash on the left side of the lower neck (just above the shoulder) which extended from the left-side of the neck towards the center of neck, at night (i.e. 11:45 pm). The intensity of redness had reduced in the next 30 min or so and the rash was nearly gone by the next day morning.  Final outcomes: The allergic reaction symptoms that I had developed after taking the first dose of Covid-19 vaccine from Pfizer-BioNTech had mostly resolved on their own in a week. I did not take any medications to help relieve the allergy symptoms.   Concerns and queries:  1) Would it be safe for me to take a second dose of Covid-19 vaccine from Pfizer-BioNTech?  2) Would an anti-allergy medication be helpful to take before receiving a second dose of Covid-19 vaccine from Pfizer-BioNTech?  3) Is it safe to receive a Covid-19 vaccine from a different company (e.g. Johnson & Johnson or Novavax)? I am presently partially vaccinated.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient said she felt dizzy after receiving the Moderna vaccine.  It was her first immunization.  This occured at 4:42pm.  She did not feel better after 30 minutes so we offered her to come into the pharmacy and lay down.  We took her blood pressure and blood sugar.  Her BP was 113/73.  Her BS was 108.  After about 20min, she said that she felt cold.  Shortly after this, she said that her throat felt strange.  She said that she thought it was swelling.  She began to have difficulty breathing.  At that time, an epinephrine 0.3mg auto injection was given at 6pm.  The pt began to breathe easier within a minute of the injection.  The pt said that she felt tingling in her legs and hands.  After about 10 minutes, she said that feeling in her throat was coming back.  At that time, the ambulence attendants arrived.  We told them about giving one injection of the epi-pen.  The ambulence attendents were able to walk the pt to the gurney.
OTHER_MEDS: Lamictal 150mg Cyclobenzaprine 5mg Levothyroxine 125mcg Meloxicam 7.5mg Clonazepam2mg Estradiol 1mg

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I was alone.  I have little memory of the early a.m. hours after the vaccination.  I wasn't cold but was trembling so I thought the bones in the roof of my mouth were cracking.  It took me hours to get up and get to the kitchen to get tylenol which was impossible with the trembling.  I had a 100.8 fever, though the thermometer didn't really stay in my mouth.  I was extremely short of breath.  All of my nail beds were blue.  I honestly don't remember all details of that round of after effects other than that I could barely walk.  The next afternoon when I sort of came-to I noted I'd used 22 inhalations on my albuteral inhaler the hours I was in bed, I don't remember using it.  I had the zaps all day and the next night.  I woke with a migraine early am the next morning to the point of almost vomiting, I've not vomited in 15 years.  I don't get migrains but for a few back in my 20's.  I had some SOB and headache on and off and dizziness persists.  there is more, but my greatest concern is the SOB and clear oxygen issue I had with the blue nail beds.  I believe I wasn't thinking nor remembering due to that. Had my adult aged kids been here I suspect they'd have called me an ambulance.  I wish they had been as I remember being terrified not being able to get up, but I just kept trying to sleep a bit more.  There needs to be a MUCH better check system here for people.  Maybe even suggested not to be alone the night after the vaccination (either dose really).  I've never seen my nailbeds so blue in my life.  I've seen it on a friend once years ago, she was bleeding internally.   Headaches continue.  Oh and food does not taste right yet.  It took 2 days for anything to taste normal, but many things still don't.
OTHER_MEDS: Albuterol as needed.  Dulera morning and night daily.  Zyrtec nightly

First: April 25~27: Sore Arm, similar to a bruised muscle. Second: April 27 my right forehead just below the hairline and in the right ear area where the top of the ear meets the head, had minor itching and were turning red. On April 28. Hives began on my left arm's lower wrist and in the general area of my right leg's knee. The hives became more numerous in these areas until a general red rash condition was appearing  between them as well. By Saturday Morning May 1 the knee and wrist areas were noticeably red like a rash and hives were also appearing with itching below the right knee on the upper half of my shin, above this knee, on my right lower wrist and on my left lower fore arm.  My right ear was starting to swell at just the top. I tried putting Gold Bond Medicated Powder on these areas, but it didn't reduce the itching much.      Sunday May 2, I called my mom who is a Registered Nurse about this. She advised going to my health care provider to substantiate these symptoms. Monday May 3 I visited my health care provider's office after work and got an appointment for Tuesday at 10:15 from a cancellation. One of their RN's looked at my hives and rashes. New hives had now also formed on my left leg just below the knee on the back side. It was a red string of itching a couple inches long. I called my boss Tuesday so I could take the day off for the appointment and he agreed that I should do  this. At the doctor's office, PA-C after extensive questioning and examination said he thought this was an allergic reaction possibly related to the polyethylene content of the vaccination. He further advised that I not get the second shot until I was checked by an allergist. He put in a referral for this. I think I picked up cold-like symptoms (sore throat and cough) from the doctor's office that were minor.      Wednesday morning I had much worse symptoms. I was weak, groggy, couldn't think without great effort, was more itchy, and my right knee was starting to ooze. I called my boss at work to take the day off since I was quite sure driving would be risky, and that I would have to leave work early for lack of energy. My right front thigh had a new area of hives along with my right and left fore arms. I started treating all my affected areas with Caladryl topical Analgesic and taking generic Benedryl. I had breakfast and then slept until 2:30 PM, had lunch and slept until evening. By then my forehead and right ear areas had reduced in severity. I had lost (2) days of work. The rest of the week, all my symptoms diminished. As of this writing Sunday May 9, my knee is still tender, sore, and red, and left wrist hives are still pronounced.
OTHER_MEDS: Vitamin C, Dextroamp-Amphhetamin, Fluoxietine, Vitamin D & key cofactors (Purity Products Advanced D), Fish  Oil & EPA & DHA & DPA (Purity Products Omega-3), Iron.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Within 15 mins of receiving vaccine client informed EMTs she was feeling itchiness around face. First vitals at 1630: blood pressure 138/89, pulse 129, oxygen 98%. PHN joined shortly after. Per client had anaphalaxis reaction to 1st dose Pfizer vaccine and was recommended to receive Janssen. Client with flushed face, rash on chest, neck and left arm. Client denied shortness of breath, chest pain, or trouble swallowing. PHN offered client Benadryl. Per client had pre-medicated with Benadryl 1.5hrs ago. Client informed she would we kept an additional 30 mins in observation. 1635 vitals: blood pressure 134/81, pulse 118, oxygen 98%. Client stated symptoms same, denied shortness of breath. Rash on chest, neck and left arm same, not spreading. PHN asked client if she had followed up with provider after first reaction. Per client did speak with provider and was given steroids afterwards. Medical history: Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome and mass cell activation. Current medications: Cromolyn Sodium, Clonidine, Corlanor, Klonopin, Hydrocodone, Flexeril, Metropolol, Microgestin, Singulair, Vitamin B, Vitamin B12, Claritin, Iron, Magnesium, Famotidone, Zyrtec, and Probiotic. Per client no past history of allergies to vaccines. 1640 vitals: blood pressure 123/93, pulse 108, oxygen 97%. Per client itchiness resolved, rash to chest, neck improving. Vitals at 1650: blood pressure 121/79, pulse 100, oxygen 98%. Per client throat felt "weird", denied shortness of breath, closing of throat, no swelling of tongue. Client able to answer all questions and breathing normal. Per client itchiness was resolved. Rash to chest and neck resolved, left arm with improved rash. 1655 vitals: blood pressure 110/80, pulse 95, oxygen 98%. Per client feeling much better. Denied shortness of breath, no itchiness, rash resolved. Client given ER precautions. Per client not driving, was getting picked up. Client left facility with steady gait at 1705.
OTHER_MEDS: Cromolyn sodium, clonidine, corlanor, kloponin, hydrocodone, flexeril, metoprolol, microgestin, singulaor, vitamin B, b12, claritin, iron, magnesium, famotidine, zyrtec

After the first vaccine, at 5am the next morning, my blood pressure dropped to 90/65 causing my vision to blackout/feel like I was going to faint, and feel like I was going to throw up when standing. I stayed flat in bed the whole day and the second day after (4/8/21), it subsided. After the second vaccine on 4/27/21, it was a much more significant response. This occurred again at about 5am the morning after the vaccine (4/28, less than 12 hours after), my blood pressure began to fall and I was experiencing orthostatic hypotension again.  On 4/29 significant body aches and pains (flu like symptoms set in). On Friday 4/30/21, I woke up, and without moving, the room was spinning, I felt like I was going to throw up, had bad headaches, and I was extremely dizzy. I took my blood pressure at it was 80/50. I could not stand or sit up, I had to lay flat with my legs propped up to keep blood flow to my head. I missed work from 4/28-5/1 as I was so hypotensive and symptomatic. I called my cardiologists office on the afternoon of 4/30 to get their advice and confirm that I should NOT take my hypertension and tachycardia medications that night (verapamil and metoprolol). The nurse advised me not to take them that day and to go to the hospital since I was so symptomatic. My mom, a cardiac care nurse, was with me at home, so I decided to stay home and only go in if it dropped any lower. The next day (Saturday) it began to normalize to around 110/70 and Sunday I was 120/80. I did not take any medication Saturday or Sunday, because I did not want my pressure to go low again. Monday I contacted my cardiologists office again, because I was still reading normal with no meds in my system, but was beginning to get chest pains related to the withdrawal from metoprolol, so they had me take the verapamil and metoprolol in normal doses Monday afternoon. Tuesday, I woke up low again (100/60) and had to call off work again. I contacted my cardiologist again, and he advised me to stop verapamil until my pressure got more high and I needed it again and called in a lower dose of my metoprolol (half the strength of what I was taking). It is now 5/9/21 and my pressure is still about 125/85, so  I have not been able to resume the verapamil and am still on the half strength metoprolol.

Vaccine Adverse Event Report May 9th, 2021 Patient had an appointment for his 2nd dose of Pfizer Covid 19 vaccine on May 9th 2021at 2:45pm. His first dose of Pfizer Covid 19 vaccine was at our Pharmacy on April 16th, 2021. Patient arrived to the appointment early; patient had been waiting for the pharmacist to return from lunch. At 2:05pm, pharmacy technician, started processing paperwork. Patient appeared normal as I, pharmacy on duty, slightly took a glance while he was at Covid 19 Vaccine Check-in window. He appeared to actively talking on phone via his wireless headphone. After processing the paperwork needed for vaccination, I went over the system to ensure the provided information was adequate before it was ready for my intern to administer the shot. Once the process was completed, as usual, pharmacy intern, took the patient to Patient Health Room for immunization. After the vaccination, as I was getting off the phone with a doctor calling in a prescription, approached and told me the patient fainted right after the vaccination, she called out my name for help, but I did not hear. Later on pharmacy technician said she was close by the area but did not hear pharmacy intern. Fortunately, the pharmacy intern said she kept calling his name and patted at the patient's shoulder softly, the patient woke up, this happened just within less than 1 minute. From pharmacy intern's report, the patient shook his head vigourously, and breathed rapidly through his lips after he woke up. Pharmacy intern instructed the patient to have a seat outside the Patient Health Room for close monitoring. I then walked outside and briefly talked to the patient. Patient stated he was perfectedly fine, said in a humor way "Yes, I passed out, but I'm perfectly fine now." Based on the vaccine administration record, patient has no medical condition. He also confirmed he had lunch before coming, so I concluded the faint was not due to hypoglycemic. I offered whether he needed anything just know that we are here. I also reassured patient to stay at least 15 minutes before he was ready to head out. it seemed like patient was actively on the phone or listened to music via his wireless headphone as I occasionally glanced at him via the mirror. Approximately 15 minutes later, patient checked in at the consultation window asking whether it was okay for him to leave. I asked him again if he was sure and felt well; he confirmed. In addition, I verified his phone number so we could call him for follow-up if needed. Shortly after the patient left, as I was ready to report the incident, I noticed his address is not within our area. I gave him a call, he answered and confirmed his address, he also said he is doing fine, just arrived at his apartment. Each team members who were involved in the event wrote the reports and kept them filed in the pharmacy records.

On April 18 and 19, following my 2nd injection, I had very bad chills and could not get warm. I was nauseous although I did not vomit. On April 22, I began having severe sharp stabbing pains just to the right of my belly button. It felt like I was being stabbed with a very hot knife, and after about 15-90 seconds, it would go away. Anytime I reached for something, bent over, twisted, turned or tried to hug someone, I would get this same pain and it would double me over in pain.  On Monday April 26 at 7pm, I finally checked into the Emergency Room  at the direction of my Primary Doctor.  They did a bunch of blood work on me and sent me for a CT Scan of my abdomen.  All of the blood work came back in normal ranges, and the CT Scan showed my appendix was "borderline" according to the surgeon. They consulted with Dr and decided to admit me for a surgical consult and further examination.  They gave me fluids and morphine through an IV for the first 24 - 36 hrs, and then switched to Norco by mouth. I continued having pain throughout my stay.  On Thursday, April 29, they took me to surgery for "exploratory surgery" with the intention of removing my appendix and looking around to see if anything else stood out to them that would cause me this pain.  They stated my appendix had scar tissue on it and they removed it, but said they did not know if this would stop the pain I was having.  On Friday April 30, I was released from the hospital at approximately 6pm.  By 9pm on Friday, I began having those same sharp, stabbing, burning pains in my abdomen again, now to the right of my belly button again and further towards my right side.  I also had sharp burning pain in the inside of my upper right arm, between my bicep and tricep muscles.  This pain continued on through the weekend occurring more frequently and more severe.  On Monday morning at about 1:30am, I woke up with severe abdominal pains all over and went into the bathroom.  I had diarrhea and nausea and felt like I was going to vomit.  Between 1:30am and 7:30am, I went to the bathroom 6 times.  I went to work on Monday and continued having abdominal pains and diarrhea all day and night.  On Tuesday, I went to the bathroom a total of 17 times. On Wednesday, I saw my primary Dr.,  who examined my abdomen and pains.  He suggested I take immodium for the diarrhea and a supplement for muscle pain, as he felt this was the cause of my pain. On Wednesday, I went to the bathroom 21 times and was very nauseaus.  I started the Imodium and it had no effect on me whatsoever.  On Thursday, I had to call off work because I couldn't stop using the bathroom.  By 4pm, I had been to the bathroom 18 times.  I returned to the ER.  They took a stool sample and did an ultrasound in the ER.  They decided to admit me again for surgical consult and pain management.  On Friday, Dr ordered another ultrasound of my abdomen, specifically my gallbladder, kidney, and liver.  He also sent me for a CT Scan with contrast.  They completed a total lab workup of my blood.  All of these results came back normal, and nothing on the images showed anything wrong with my organs.   On Saturday May 8, Dr came to the hospital to examine me. He stated everything related to my GI was fine.  He asked if I have back pain, which I told him I do.  At this time, I was in extreme pain and I couldn't even touch my skin. Dr attempted to examine my abdomen, and just by placing his hand on my stomach, I screamed in pain.  He then put his hand behind my back and pushed a little, and it cause extreme pain in my abdomen.  At this time, Dr suggested that maybe the pain is caused by something going on in my back.  Maybe a pinched nerve or something.  He ordered an X-ray of my upper and lower spine.  Later that day, the results of the X-ray came back and showed there was nothing wrong with my spine.  With these results, Dr then ordered an MRI of my lumbar and thoracic spine.  On Sunday May 9 at 1030am, I was taken to radiology for an MRI.  The initial report shows that I do not have any pinched nerves and nothing notable that would cause this type of pain in my body.   As of now, no diagnosis or explanation for the pain I am experiencing. The pain is gradually getting worse and at times I am unable to move at all without extreme severe pain in my body.  At times, my right groin hurts and I am unable to stand on my feet, as it feels as if I have pulled a groin muscle.  The pain in my abdomen takes my breath away and feels like I am being set on fire in that area of my body.  The pain no longer goes away and is constant, but moves throughout my right side from my groin to my shoulder only.  I am not able to put my right arm behind my back because I get this pain in the back of my shoulder area.  This pain is only on my right side at this time.  So far, there is no explanation for this pain.  I never had anything like this until I got the vaccine.
LAB_DATA: Blood work. April 22 - April 27 and May 6 - May 9 CT Scan x2  April 22 and May 7 Ultrasound x2 May 6 and May 7 X-ray May 8 MRI May 9

On 07May21 at 11:00PM, I experienced an immense pain on both of my arms that I've never experienced before in my life. Every time I move my arms, fingers, or apply any amount of pressure on any part of my arms, I will get a surge of pain raining down on my arms and only my arms from the shoulder down. At the same time, I also felt a surge of energy/adrenaline flowing throughout my legs, from the pelvis down, urging me to move around. I tried to force myself to sleep (without medication, just forcefully closing my eyes and trying to sleep) to no avail, so I got up and walked around my room and did some leg squats exercises without moving my arms too much from 11:10PM till 3:10AM, (I think getting my blood pumping throughout my body helped ease the pain a bit). The intensity of the pain on my arms decreased about half at around 3:10AM and I was finally able to fall asleep at around 3:30AM. I woke up once at around 7:45AM to go to the bathroom and drink some water. During this time, I think the intensity of the pain had dropped to 1/3 from when I first experienced this pain. I fell back asleep again and woke up at around 11:20AM. Most of the pain is gone by now, I only felt the lingering stings of the dreadful night from before. I continued to feel this phantom pain on both of my arms throughout the day and it wasn't until the day afterwards on the morning of 09May21 that relief was finally bestowed upon me.

minimal pericardial effusion; my oxygen saturation again plummeted/getting difficult to maintain my oxygen level during the day; mild arm pain; This spontaneous case was reported by a consumer (subsequently medically confirmed) and describes the occurrence of HYPOXIA (my oxygen saturation again plummeted/getting difficult to maintain my oxygen level during the day) and PERICARDIAL EFFUSION (minimal pericardial effusion) in a 69-year-old female patient who received mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (batch nos. 026A21A and 03IL20A) for COVID-19 vaccination. The occurrence of additional non-serious events is detailed below.     The patient's past medical history included Hypoxia. Concurrent medical conditions included Pulmonary hypertension (Reporter states: Pulmonologists disagree about this diagnosis) since May 2019 and Sleep apnea since March 2019. Concomitant products included LORATADINE for Allergy, VITAMIN D3 and CYANOCOBALAMIN (VITAMIN B12 [CYANOCOBALAMIN]) for Deficiency vitamin.   On 05-Feb-2021 at 10:30 AM, the patient received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) 1 dosage form. On 05-Mar-2021 at 10:30 AM, received second dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) dosage was changed to 1 dosage form. On 05-Mar-2021,  after starting mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine), the patient experienced PAIN IN EXTREMITY (mild arm pain). On 07-Mar-2021, the patient experienced HYPOXIA (my oxygen saturation again plummeted/getting difficult to maintain my oxygen level during the day) (seriousness criterion medically significant). On an unknown date, the patient experienced PERICARDIAL EFFUSION (minimal pericardial effusion) (seriousness criterion medically significant). At the time of the report, HYPOXIA (my oxygen saturation again plummeted/getting difficult to maintain my oxygen level during the day) and PERICARDIAL EFFUSION (minimal pericardial effusion) had not resolved and PAIN IN EXTREMITY (mild arm pain) outcome was unknown.      DIAGNOSTIC RESULTS (normal ranges are provided in parenthesis if available): On 07-Mar-2021, Oxygen saturation: low (Low) Low. On 17-Apr-2021, Brain natriuretic peptide: 1064 (High) "nearly 10 times the normal limit and is a strong indicator of heart failure". On 29-Apr-2021, Computerised tomogram thorax: abnormal (abnormal) minimal pericardial effusion.         Reporter states: I was diagnosed two years ago with sleep apnea and nocturnal hypoxia and have used a CPAP device with oxygen every night since. Following the first dose of the vaccine, my oxygen level was so low that I had to go onto daytime supplemental oxygen for the first time. It is getting difficult to maintain my oxygen level during the day even with supplemental oxygen. The cardiologist has ordered an echocardiogram for May 7, 2021. SYMPTOM_TEXT: the patient only received the IPV and DTAP and not the HIB portion, with no reported adverse event; Initial information regarding an unsolicited valid non-serious case was received from the other health professional (nurse) via medical information (MI) (Reference number- 00577376) and transmitted to Sanofi on 26-Apr-2021.  This case involves a 7 month old male patient who only received the IPV and DTAP and not the HIB portion, while patient received a third dose of suspect DIPHTHERIA/TETANUS/5 HYBRID AC PERTUSSIS/IPV(MRC5)/HIB(PRP/T) VACCINE [PENTACEL] [lot number: UJ336AA, expiry date and other dosing details were not reported] on 24-Mar-2021 for prophylactic vaccination (product preparation issue).  Medical history, medical treatment, vaccination and family history were not reported.  Concomitant vaccinations included ROTAVIRUS VACCINE (ROTAVIRUS VACCINE) and PNEUMOCOCCAL VACCINE 13V (PNEUMOCOCCAL VACCINE 13V) (PNEUMOC 13,).  It was a case of actual medication error due to inappropriate reconstitution technique. (Latency: same day)  It was reported that, while doing inventory, reporter discovered an extra vial of Act HIB in a Pentacel box.   It was also reported that, recently the have had vaccinated 2 children in last 2-3 weeks with Pentacel but they could not tell which child only got the IPV/DTaP vial and not the powder Act HIB vial.   At the time of reporting, reporter was not sure that, the patient details reported for child that one if only IPV/DTAP portion and not the HIB portion of Pentacel or not.   About lot number it was reported that, the way they document the lot for Pentacel, it was reported to her.   At the time of report, no adverse event was reported.   This suspected adverse reaction report is submitted and classified as a medication error solely and exclusively to ensure the marketing authorization holder's compliance with the requirements set out in the Directive 2001/83/EC and Module VI of the Good Pharmacovigilance Practices. The classification as a medical error is in no way intended, nor should it be interpreted or construed as an allegation or claim made by the marketing authorization holder that any third party has contributed to or is to be held liable for the occurrence of this medication error.

The patient had overlapping stuff from cervical stenosis that manifested on the left side on his shoulder arm and hands, droopy mouth, eye wouldn't close, vertigo, ear issues, hearing drop. His eye had the feeling like it couldn't close his eyelids at night the muscles in his face on the left side face felt taut. The inside of his gum felt like his skin was thicker, he was not sure it was or wasn't but that was the sensation and that never went away and down the side of his tongue was tingly. These things overlap and it was either very little or really annoying. it was just annoying on and off and after the shot on Sunday it was weird at first, he was writing it off as both stress and relief and other things. He wasn't dizzy, he waited for 15 minutes and went home and after and that evening the left side of his mouth went bonkers, it wound up being like when the shingles were acting up on the inside of his mouth it felt tingly and weird and it was confined to the left half of his face and nothing else. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Chills and fever began about 8 hrs after second shot on Friday afternoon. Normal baseline temp is 97 - temp was up to 101.5 overnight/early Saturday morning. Symptoms predominantly fever and fatigue all day Saturday, with temp hovering around 100.7-101.5 during the day. I expected symptoms like this based on others' experiences. The reason I am reporting is that I briefly passed out right around the 24 hour mark. I had eaten very little (a banana and two eggs that morning) but was drinking a fair amount of fluids, and had basically slept most of the day. Around 1:30PM, I woke up, took my temperature, and was surprised to see it read 101.5 - I felt cooler or at least I felt less uncomfortably warm than I had when it read higher. I got up, reheated some soup, and just as I was pouring it in the bowl, was hit with an overwhelming wave of nausea and dizziness such that I thought I wouldn't make it to the bathroom. En route, I bumped into a piece of furniture with my right arm. I remember grabbing my arm and the next thing I knew, I was lying on the hallway floor. I must have slid down somehow, because I didn't have any head pain or bump to the head - and managed to get to the bathroom. After a time, the nausea passed without vomiting, I made it back to bed, fell asleep, and felt better enough when I woke two hours later to eat some soup. I continued to drink a lot of fluids and had a smoothie before bed. My temperature peaked at 102.3 that night before bed. Overnight Saturday, I sweat through two shirts. My temperature Sunday morning was 99.1 and I noticed some low-level "COVID rash" at my injection site before bed Sunday night. I woke this morning (Monday) at 5AM to discover I had sweat through another shirt, but my temp was finally back to 97.1. Again, I wouldn't have reported this as out of the ordinary, if I hadn't briefly passed out. I should say that Saturday (day after my shot) was also the first full day of my period. SYMPTOM_TEXT: 34 y/o male with no known medical history, who presents with seizure like activity lasting 2-3 seconds post vaccination. Patient states that this is his second vaccination in the two-dose series. Patient denies previous reaction with the first vaccination. Patient states that he fears needles. Patient was witnessed with upper arm stiffening, convulsions and syncope lasting 2-3 seconds. RNs lowered patient to the ground with legs elevated. Patient regained consciousness within seconds. Patient was not post ictal. Patient denies headache, sore throat, difficulty breathing or itch. Patient vitals (151/79 BP, 98% O2, 74 HR, 14 Resp, Glucose 125, EKG NSR). Fire rescue was called. Patient was placed in wheelchair and taken to private area where he was further assessed by the Paramedics, NP and RN. Patient was noted to be diaphoretic. Water provided and patient placed in Trendelenburg position. Fire rescue arrived. Patient refused to be transported to the ER, although it was advised by the NP. Fire rescue did not have the patient sign out AMA. AMA form provided and signed, witnessed by the NP. Patient aware of risk involved with no seeking further medical evaluation, such as worsening adverse reaction, subsequent seizures, cardiac event, MVA and/or death. Patient verbalized understanding. Patient ambulated to his car without difficulty.

On 20 Jan 2021, 8 days after immunization developed bullseye rash on L upper arm at site of injection and nodular/papular dermatitits on anterior thiges bilaterally. Was seen by urgent care on 20 Jan 2021 and prescribed prednisone 20mg daily x 5 days. L upper arm lesion resolved after 3 days but anterior thigh lesions remained. She was seen by dermatology on 3 Feb 2021 and biopsy performed. Lesions described at that time as indurated erythematous to violaceous subcutaneous nodules.  Seen in follow up at dermatology 9 Feb 2021 and had intralesional steroid injections. Seen by dermatology 16 Feb 2021 as treated lesions persisted, now lesions appeared on anterior thighs and patient c/o increased pruritus. She was treated with 1st and 2nd generation H1 blockers and a 2 week prednisone taper. Biopsy consistent with  granulomatous dermatitis/panniculitis. Starting early Feb 2021, noted gradually worening symptoms of dyspnea on exertion.  Seen by pulmonologist who ordered a chest CT and subsequently diagnosed with pulmonary embolus. She was started on abixiban daily. She was further evaluated by cardiology, hematology and rheumatology in March and April 2021. She had been on OCP at the time of diagnosis of the PE and this was changed to Nexaplan implant by Gyn. Workup with all specialists ongoing. Pulmonology recently added Fluticasone/Salmeterol inhaler which she finds has not improved her dyspnea.
LAB_DATA: Biopsy of anterior thigh lesions consistent with  granulomatous dermatitis/panniculitis. Chest CT c/w pulmonary embolus
OTHER_MEDS: Fexofenadine 180mg daily, Cetirizine 10mg daily, Vit D, Calcium, OCP, EpiPen

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Woke up around 3AM in chills and a cold sweat. Was unable to fall back asleep until around 7:30AM--didn't check my temperature until about 8AM, and it was 103.4 degrees. My temperature peaked at 104.1 later that morning. I took Ibuprofen, stayed in bed, kept a cold cloth on my forehead, and drank a lot of water in the meantime. My fever started to come down in the afternoon, but did seem to climb if I wasn't adamant about keeping a cold cloth on my forehead--for example, it would come down to about 100, but if I took of the cloth for about 30 minutes, it started to climb back up toward 102. My fever seemed to break around 4 or 5PM, but I slept most of the day, so I don't have an exact time. After that, I had a little "brain fog" for the rest of the evening (Friday, April 7th), but when I woke Saturday (April 8th) I felt almost totally recovered.

Pinprick and temperature sensation were normal. Left biceps reflex was 1+; all other UE reflexes were 2+. EMG/NCS done and consistent with mild lower trunk brachial plexopathy. MRI done and shows enhancement in the scalene muscle just adjacent to lower brachial plexus. Presentation felt consistent with Parsonage Turner syndrome, brachial neuritis. He was treated with a one week prednisone taper. Over the next 3 months, he has had gradual improvement in strength and sensation. Only minimal deficits remain.

He felt very bad the night he received the 2nd shot of Pfizer covid-19 vaccine on April 27. He even joked he probably would die that night. He also complained that despite his protest, the person who administered the shot insisted to inject on his shoulder joint.  He developed a bigger-than-quarter-size bruise on his right inner arm the next day. He was feeling tired the following days. On May 4 around 3:30, I heard he was making loud noises. I came to his side immediately. At the time I thought he was making louder than usual snores. I nudged him gently but he didn't respond.  After about 15 seconds, the sound stopped, and he had no breath. I then called 911 within 10 seconds, tried to do CPR on him. It took EMS 6 minutes to arrive even though we live very close to a fire station in a well-accessed urban area. EMS worked on him for about 30 minutes before transported him to hospital. They continued to work on him for a while. He never regained breath.
LAB_DATA: On May 4, office call me in the afternoon. They told me their autopsy indicated he had an enlarged heart and a defective valve.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: From ED note:  Briefly, this is a 23-year-old female with past medical history of not allergies, asthma who presents for evaluation of shortness of breath, nausea and chest discomfort following Covid vaccine 30 minutes prior to presentation.  Patient received her first dose of Pfizer Covid vaccine this morning, was observed and ultimately started to drive home with mother when she developed shortness of breath, nausea and chest discomfort.  These have been progressive.  She reports she is not taking her Flovent.  No vomiting, no rash, no weakness, headache or dizziness. Remainder of history per note above.   Vital signs as noted above (tachycardia, tachypneic).  On physical exam, the patient is anxious appearing, hyperventilating; HEENT exam with MMM, clear conjunctivae, normal TMs & clear oropharynx without uvular swelling or edema; neck is supple; cardiovascular exam is stable with regular rhythm, mild tachycardia, no murmurs; pulmonary exam is clear to auscultation bilaterally, good aeration, no wheezes; abdomen is soft, non-tender & non-distended; neurologic exam nonfocal, moves all four extremities, 5/5 strength in upper and lower extremities, carpal spasm of bilateral hands (L>R).   My impression is that this patient is having a panic attack given her rapid onset of hyperventilation, chest discomfort, and bilateral carpal spasms. Carpal spasms improved with controlled breathing. Considered anaphylaxis given patient's history, but absolutely no wheezing, rash or significant GI symptoms; no hypoxia; no hypotension. Epi-pen at bedside, but not given. Considered asthma, but no wheezing - patient is not wheezing and has good aeration on exam, she is requesting albuterol, which I think will help with her anxiety surrounding this - 2 puffs given. No evidence of persistent tachycardia to suggest PE (no OCPS). Initial ECG with sinus arrhythmia, one PVC, slightly prolonged QTc 477 - will check repeat. Patient briefly on NRB for comfort - slowly able to be weaned off and during observation in ED, symptoms improving but not completely resolved. Repeat ECG w/ NSR, slightly prolonged QTc 460. Given persistence of symptoms, patient given epi-pen and had almost complete resolution of symptoms within 10 minutes. We will plan to observe for 4 hours post-epi administration. Recommended discussion of second COVID vaccine with primary care provider but may have to avoid given this could have represented a serious allergic reaction. Recommend follow-up with PCP/cardiology for repeat EKG.   Admit to Ed Observation Status  Diagnosis: Allergic reaction  Goals of observation: (1) Ensure continued improvement of symptoms, (2) Improved HR  Interventions: (1) CRM, (2) Close monitoring, (3) Frequent exams  5/7/2021  15:00   23-year-old female received COVID-19 vaccine today and after which developed shortness of breath.  Initially felt this was anxiety however symptoms persisted.  Treated with albuterol as well as epinephrine and observed.  Developed shortness of breath and complaints of chest pain after approximately 3 hours of observation.  Repeat EKG obtained and is normal.  Labs were obtained which demonstrated normal CBC.  Normal D-dimer.  Normal electrolytes but an elevated TSH (known hyperthyroidism).  Treated with cetirizine and steroids with improvement of her symptoms.  Discharged with PCP follow-up in 2 days.
LAB_DATA: EKG - slightly prolonged QTc 477, repeat normal CBC - normal TSH - elevated 5.66 (known hypothyroidism) D-dimer - normal Chem7 - normal
HISTORY: Hypothyroidism, history of asthma, tree nut and milk allergies that caused GI symptoms with no h/o anaphylaxis.

Patient presented to the ED about an hour after receiving COVID vaccination. Per ED notes, " She experienced facial flushing, chest tightness and difficulty breathing.  She has a history of multiple allergies. Her chest feels tight but she has not been hearing herself wheeze she has been coughing quite a bit.  She denies throat tightness.  She feels hot and lightheaded.  She is noticed that her face is red.   Patient was given 50 mg of Benadryl p.o. and 40 mg of prednisone p.o. as well as an albuterol neb.  The albuterol neb gave her significant relief from the chest tightness and I reexamined her lung and she still has no wheezing and she is moving air well.  Sats have been fine the whole time she has been here the facial flushing diminished steadily.  The patient did not want a wait for any more than an hour and a half.  She states she is feeling much better.  I will give her a prescription for prednisone, 5 days and an EpiPen."

I had the same sore arm, head ache, body aches, fatigue after the second dose as I did after the first dose.  However on day 5 I developed the worst fever blister on my lower lip.  On day 13 I experienced an anaphylactic episode. I noticed my hands started itching about 30 mintues after eating breakfast (coffee, oatmeal, blueberries, almonds).  I took my dog for a walk and started to feel nausaus and extremely tired.  I went to bed. Hives started.   Had abdominal cramps,  loose stool.  Took benadryl 25 mg. then another 25 mg.  Initially felt better after taking the benadryl.  About 30 minutes later, more nausea and cramps.  I went to the bathroom and while sitting on the toilet I could tell I was going to pass out.  I lay down on the floor and was competely weak.  I was aware that my bowels were moving, but I could do nothing about it.  I was able to call for my husband (approximately 20 minutes later).  He called an ambulance.  Blood work from ER was normal except for WBC 15.4,  Neutrophils 88.9%, Lymphocytes 6.6%, Eosinophils 0.1%,  ANC 13.8,  absolute granulocytes 13.7, glucose 152, and MPV 9.2,  I saw an allergist because they thought I had developed a food allergy but that was ruled out.  I have an epi pen now.
CUR_ILL: I developed a terrible fever blister on my lower lip on day 5 after the vaccine (2-19-2021).  It had not resolved when I had this anaphylaxis episode

SYMPTOM_TEXT: DVT, LLE pain, occlusive thrombus
LAB_DATA: lower extremity duplex US 3/26/2021  Entry Date and Time Status Entered by 3/26/2021  5:06 PM Final result Edi, Rad Results In Narrative & Impression Examination: Left lower extremity venous Doppler study. History: Left lower extremity swelling. Pain Comparison: No prior imaging for comparison Technique and findings: Gray scale, color, and pulsed Doppler were done.  The bilateral external iliac veins demonstrates normal respiratory variability without occlusive thrombus. The common femoral, profunda femoral, and proximal femoral veins demonstrate patency on grayscale and color Doppler. There is nonocclusive thrombus in the mid femoral vein with occlusive thrombus noted in the distal femoral vein, popliteal, tibioperoneal trunk, and posterior tibial veins. The peroneal vein is not visualized suspicious for occlusive thrombus. The bilateral posterior tibial and peroneal veins in the calf are unremarkable without evidence of venous thrombosis.     Impression: Nonocclusive thrombus in the mid femoral vein with occlusive thrombus noted from the distal femoral vein down to the level of the posterior tibial veins. The peroneal veins are not visualized and this is suspicious for occlusive thrombus. This clot does expand the vein although in part is echogenic. Therefore, a component of chronic or subacute DVT cannot entirely be excluded. However, no prior images are available for comparison and I do not know for how long the patient has been symptomatic. Additionally, acute thrombus is more likely to expand the vein as noted here. Thus, I suspect that at least some of this thrombus is acute. There is a relatively large clot burden.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Swelling, hardness, itchiness, redness, soreness around injection site. By the next morning (Saturday 5/8) it had spread to about 3 inches in diameter and was red and itchy. 29 hours post injection diameter was roughly the same but the lump protruded more and was harder, bright red, extremely tender to the touch, and itchy. It felt as if the skin might tear. The next morning  (Sunday 5/9) the redness and soreness dulled but were still present, and all other symptoms remained the same the remainder of the day. Monday morning, 5/10, diameter has increased to roughly 4 inches but the bump does not protrude as much as it used to and the redness has dulled substantially. It still remains itchy and hard, though the tenderness has slightly subsided.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The evening of Wednesday I began feeling chest pressure/discomfort and slight difficulty breathing. The same on Thursday, but a little worse. Friday morning at 4:30am I awoke from intense pain and pressure in my chest, difficulty breathing, and back/shoulder/neck pain. I went to the ER at 7:30 in the morning. Had tests taken, was given colchicine to help with the pain, and it did help lower the pain level a little bit. By Noon the pain was tolerable enough that I could go home. I was told to take ibuprofen to manage the pain. I took a nap but awoke at 2:30pm, this time with even more intense pain, my back/neck/shoulder muscles convulsing/twitching from pain and from being in a state of involuntary clenching as well as chest pain/pressure and difficulty breathing. I went back to the ER and after several more tests, an ECG gave the doctors cause to worry about the health of my heart (they were concerned I may be having a heart attack or heart failure). They kept me overnight and after taking more blood tests and ECG tests were able to diagnose me with Pericarditis on Saturday morning. I was prescribed colchicine, which I am to take twice a day for three months and ibuprofen to manage the pain.

LAB_DATA: 39 yo male with no significant medical history but family history of blood clotting disorders who presented to the ED with R sided weakness, R facial droop, R CN 6 palsy, and dysarthria. MRI showed small acute ischemic infarct in ventromedial L thalamus and chronic bilateral cerebellar lacunar infarcts. Patient received tPA as he was within the tPA window. Patient was admitted to neuro ICU for acute ischemic stroke with concern for blood clotting disorder. Showed mprovement in symptoms s/p tPA. 2D echo revealed PFO, ongoing discussions for closure device as per specialists. Pending hemonc workup for thrombophilias and vasculitis. I ate a normal breakfast with protein and carb and my normal dose of caffeine in the morning. Within 10 min of getting the vaccine my head was splitting and pounding so badly I talked to the nurse. I have had a migraine before, but this was different and unlike any headache I ever have had. Lights did not bother me, but sounds were harsher. The frontal lobe of my head is where it hurt, not in my temples and not anywhere else.  The pounding was so bad I was nauseous and dizzy feeling. I was told to go home and take tylenol and I did so. I use arthritis tylenol which is the strongest and I took 2 but it didn't help take away the pain. Sleeping helped some, which was surprising as I have never been able to sleep with any headache or migraine before.  The headache lasted throughout that first day, throughout the second day and mostly through the third day. It started to lesson around 9pm on the third day. By this time I had tried naproxyn, ibuprophen, and tylenol (i am allergic to asprin). Nothing helped what so ever.  On the fourth day the much milder headache still lingered and on the fifth day it was finally gone.  The nausea and dizziness lasted the entire first day and through part of the second day.  I am someone who walks on broken bones and stage 5 avascular necrosis without complaint. I am labelled someone who doesn't feel the same amount of pain as most people do. It is common for me to hurt myself and not even know it until someone points it out.  So pain I can normally handle, I also have techniques to lesson pain that I use every day, but nothing helped this headache.  As someone who dislocated her finger and popped it back in myself and went back to cooking immediately... The headache was not manageable. I tried Everything I know to do.  I actually felt like my brain was on fire and going to explode. I was concerned enough to talk to a nurse, which is also something I would not do if it did not feel like that.  When I get a migraine and the lights hurt my eyes, I pop on some glasses and continue onward. Not a big deal.   But with whatever happened to my brain that day, I'd say 90% would have ended up in the emergency room. But I prefer to handle things on my own.
HISTORY: severe and chronic Asthma, avascular necrosis

SYMPTOM_TEXT: PT was administered the Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine at 11:10am and waited with wife and daughter in the designated waiting area. They walked to the store entryway to leave at 11:30am and Pt complained of nausea. His daughter brought him a garbage can; he retched into it twice without vomiting. He then arched back and started seizing. He was seated in a walker at the time, went very pale and seized for approximately 30-40 seconds. Emergency services were contacted by store personnel. We laid him down on the ground to decrease his fall risk. Approximately 5 minutes later he was verbal and responsive. EMS arrived and took over. I informed them of his vaccination and daughter relayed his health history. EMS then took patient to preferred hospital for evaluation.
HISTORY: He is diabetic (BS ~140 around 10:00am after eating a banana and banana bread), has cerebral palsy, is undergoing radiation for cancer, history of kidney transplant, and has a history of seizures secondary to a stroke caused by TPA after a heart attack.

We were monitoring him and he informed us that it was anxiety related. He couldn't move his hands and started blacking out. When EMT arrived he started to feel better. They were able to rule out an allergic reaction and it was most likely anxiety related. Patient refused to go to the hospital and was walked out by EMT to make sure he could drive home.

Approximately 20-30 seconds after receiving the shot, my blood pressure dropped, my heart rate accelerated, my face was pale while the rest of my body was flushed and I broke out in a cold sweat. I instantly felt light headed and my ears felt plugged. I was instructed to lay my head down and was given a juice and cookie.  At the time, I was told it was syncope and it was ?normal.?  The symptoms resided after approx 5 minutes, but I continued to feel very out of it for the rest of the day. Since then, I?ve been told those are signs of cardiac anaphylaxis and my doctor encouraged me to report it to VAERS and not get the second dose.  I give blood samples regularly and get my flu shot and have never had this reaction, so I know this was not a ?fear of needles.?

Her pupils were dilated and slow to react and she was in some respiratory distress and very diaphoretic.  At this point airway was controlled 5 oh endotracheal intubation using the glide scope and during the intubation patient was noted for copious amounts of dark brown vomitus coming from her esophagus which was guaiac positive.  Her blood pressure was low she was sedated initially with propofol etomidate was used for the intubation however because of her hypotension the propofol was slowed and she was given Versed which did seem to control her agitation and maintain her blood pressure.  Patient had IV fluid initiated wide open and CT scan was obtained of head chest abdomen pelvis given the fact that her altered mental status could be from some kind of intracerebral catastrophe and the patient's abdominal exam being unobtainable certainly possible that her GI bleeding could be from a perforated viscus. Her blood pressure continued to decline and Levophed was instituted.  Case was discussed in detail with surgery and she will go to the OR immediately.  Her temperature continued to rise and was 104.5 upon transfer to the operating room as blood pressure was 78 systolic      CRITICAL CARE: o Critical Care Indication patient was critically ill...  o Critical Care Indication Patient was critically ill with a high probability of imminent or life threatening deterioration. o Critical Care Time Spent 75-104 minutes (1 hour 15 minutes-1 hour 44 minutes)  2 hours and 50 minutes    ED WORKING DIAGNOSIS:   Perforated abdominal viscus (R19.8): Status: Active  Septic shock (A41.9): Status: Active    DISCHARGE/ADMISSION/TRANSFER DISPOSITION: o Disposition admitted  o Admit To To OR    CONDITION ON DISCHARGE/ADMISSION/TRANSFER: o Condition Critical  Date of OR Procedure  o Date of Procedure 05/10/2021 10:01  Pre Op Dx, Post Op Dx, Procedure  o Pre Operative Diagnosis: Perforated viscus o Post Operative Diagnosis: Ischemic bowel, most likely from shower emboli.  Most of the small intestine and large intestine was affected. o Procedure: Exploratory laparotomy, ICG injection for evaluation of perfusion  Indication and Consent  Findings: . Findings: Even after the ICG injection.  There was spotty tissue necrosis from mid jejunum all the way through sigmoid colon.  Most areas were blackened with a foul smell.  There was some highlighted areas secondary to the ICG but not a significant amount that would lend for an anastomosis.  Black ascites was present throughout the abdomen.  Unfortunately after much contemplation there was no surgical intervention.   Procedure  Procedure: Patient was placed in supine position.  Was intubated in the emergency room so, we were able to proceed with resuscitation through our anesthesia team.  Patient's abdomen was prepped and draped in usual fashion.  Proceeded to make a midline incision.  The blood supply in the subcutaneous tissues did not even bleed.  Appeared to be darkened and almost coagulated.  As we entered through the fascia we were able to open the peritoneum between 2 hemostats.  The large rush of free air through from the abdomen.  We then proceeded to open the abdomen for the length of her incision.  This was done with electrocautery.  From here there was a black ascites present within the abdomen.  There was a large amount of dead intestine that we could immediately see.  I worked my way to the ligament of Treitz.  There was no adhesions so this was easily found.  That intestine did appear to be pink.  It lasted for about a foot.  After that area everything was either black or purple in color with a few pink spots in between.  This went all the way down to the terminal ileum where pneumatosis was visualized.  We then looked at the colon from cecum through rectum.  It appeared to be blackened as well.  Not knowing whether all of this intestine was dead or not especially with patient being hypotensive I injected ICG dye approximately 2 cc.  This was to evaluate perfusion.  Unfortunately perfusion was no better than what I could visualize.  I could not even find enough room of the colon or small intestine to make an anastomosis.  Was very hard decision, however, we did not resect any bowel.  I closed the patient's abdomen.  Patient will be taken to ICU on ventilator.  Discussed with daughter with pastor present.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: At 23:15 (7 hours after the dose) I started to get cold while under my blankets trying to sleep. My teeth began chattering as I started to shiver. I got up out of bed to put on a sweater. With each step I took towards the sweater my body started to fully shiver and contract. After about 4 or 5 steps I could no longer move and I fell over. I started having full body spasms and full contractions. I felt like I pulled every muscle in my body trying to relax and fight the contractions. It felt like I was being tasered for about 10-15 minutes. Once I had the strength to grab my sweater I slipped it on. As my body warmed up these contraction subsided.  By 01:00 (9 hours after dose) my body temperature had spiked. I didn't have a thermometer to check my temperature but I wouldn't be surprised if I spiked a fever. I placed a wet cloth on the back of my neck, forehead and chest to cool down.   At 06:00 (14 hours after dose) I took a cold shower to further drop my body's temperature. It felt like a full body sun burn where you just radiate heat. I was hot everywhere.  At 08:00 (16 hours after dose) I took three (3) 500mg ibuprofen to help fight a nagging headache. I did not have much appetite for food. I regularly eat breakfast in the morning (bowl of cereal).   From 09:00 to 12:00 (17-20 hours after dose) I felt groggy. Did not seem or act like myself. Was very tired from the lack of sleep the night prior. Seemed very fatigued.  Around 13:00 (21 hours after dose) I took a 45-60 minute nap. Woke up feeling much better. I would say most / if not all symptoms subsided after 22-24 hours.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: got second shot, moderna, same arm, left, same location. Everything went well, 1st dose just my arm hurt fo a few hours, second dose, 1 month later, same arm, I was somewhat sick, groggy, tired, slept 16 hours, then felt fine. I noticed that my shoulders were sore, like I slept wrong, but it never got better, it got worse for about a week, and has stayed bad.  I have limited range in motion in both arms.  and the pain is always there unless I take ibuprofen.  I am a diabetic, but have few if no medicals issues related to that.  I am healthy,  I manage my blood sugars, I am active and work at a school, meaning i walk around all day. I have never had joint pain in my 50 years besides sleeping on my arm  wrong.  This has not gotten better.  The things I notice are difficult is getting dressed, putting my bra on, and when I use the bathroom, the range of motion is bad.  This sucks, I am not a baby or a whiner, but after 2 months of no change in the pain, I googled it.  The description of SIRVA  is exactly what I feel day to day.  I had never heard of this before. Not sure where to go as I have an endocrynologist for my diabetes but really never hurt so no general doctor.
PCR+ on 4/6/21 after fully vaccinated

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Received my second Pfizer shot on Thursday late afternoon. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient left vaccination site after waiting 15 minutes post vaccination. Approximately 15-20 minutes later she experienced facial flushing, tingling and "itchy throat" confined to her face and neck. She returned to the vaccination site, was seated, and assessed. She denied symptoms of shortness of breath or swelling of the throat or tongue. Her radial pulse was steady and regular at 80 BPM. She denied sx of tachycardia, orthostasis. There was no audible stridor. Her BP was measured at 125/70 mm Hg. She was treated with 12.5mg of liquid diphenhydramine. This dose was repeated approximately 20 minutes later since her sx did not improve. The patient was given bottled water and consumed  approx 16 oz over the course of 30min. She was also given a cold wet face cloth for symptomatic relief of the flushing. The patient got up X2  to use the restroom w/o event - denied dizziness or orthostasis. After approx. 50 min the pt  was determined to be stable and contacted a family member to drive her home. She left the clinic without incident.
ALLERGIES: mangos - redness, tingling, minor swelling of lips and perioral area

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient was advised to remain in observation area for 30 minutes due to history of breathing difficulty with sulfa antibiotics in past. Shortly after being vaccinated the patient presented to our service window stating he did not feel well and was immediately escorted by the pharmacist to our administration area to have a seat. He stated he felt light headed, flushed (though not visibly), felt like his heart was racing, and was not having diffuculty breathing but felt like he couldn't catch his breath and stated he thought he was having a panic attack. He had stated before vaccination that he had not had a vaccine since his routing childhood schedule, his whole family had already had doses, and he had been putting it off because he was nervous. He insisted he needed some fresh air several times and was escorted outside by the pharmacist (with emergency supplies and a cell phone and within shouting distance of the pharmacy) for continued obsevation and was given water when requested. After a few minutes he stated he felt much better and the symptoms had resoved. He was directly observed outside per his request for the remainder of his waiting period and had no further symptoms. He was instructed to call the pharmacy right away if he had any additional symptoms after leaving.

The morning after Mom's first dose of the Pfizer shot, Dad woke up and found Mom lying on the floor next to the bed.  Mom said, "I can't move my arm." Dad called paramedics who checked her.  They said her vital signs were normal and left.  On 2/9/21 in the morning my da awoke to see that Mom had large amounts of bubbly saliva pouring from her mouth onto her pillow.  Dad called paramedics, who said this was a diabetic reaction.  Mom had NEVER had anything happen like this before.  Mom was very sleepy, could not be aroused, and made only gurgling noises.  She was admitted to the hospital for care and therapy.  She pulled her own IV out.  Mom had to be restrained in the hospital and sedated, due to confusion and worsening dementia.  By 2/18 when we spoke by phone mom's speech was abnormally slow and very repetitive.  "I'm very tired today" was spoken many times.  In morning time mom was able to follow basic conversation.  Not so later in the day.  Mom came home from rehab on 2/26/21.  She was able to walk steadily and independently at home after her therapy.  After a week or so, Mom began hitting the in-home caregiver.  Dad's presence would calm her.  In a short time Mom seemed not to know dad anymore, and would hit him and the caregiver when they helped her.  She also pulled all covers off the bed and pulled clothes out of the closet, throwing them all over the room during the night.  Mom was usually walking around the house during each night.  On 4/16/21 Mom and dad were napping sitting up on the couch in the morning.  Mom fell forward and hit her head on the hearth.  Dad and caregiver gave first aid and called paramedics, who took her to the ER.  Mom came home on 4/17/21.  On 4/18/21 Mom pulled her catheter out in the early morning.  In the afternoon Mom's appearance was concerning, so Dad called paramedics.  They said that Mom's BP had dropped very low and took her to the ER. Mom was combative the next day in the hospital. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Received cover shot on 3-17 and at 2am on 3-18 I woke up and could not move my left arm.  Thinking the arm was asleep, I attempted to move it with the opposite hand and extreme pain resulted from the slightest movement.  I noticed the bandage covering the injection site was high up on the shoulder about 1 finger width below the boney point of the shoulder.  I began doing daily stretches /exercises to try to regain mobility in the left arm.  After about 3 weeks there was some improvement in mobility but still pain with many movements.  I began researching arm pain following covid vaccine and discovered there can be injury caused by vaccines being injected too high, above the muscle.  I contacted my Dr's office and asked for advice on what to do next to improve my arm function.  Physical therapy was suggested.  I received my second covid dose on 4-14-21. I spoke to the RN administering the 2nd dose about my previous shot.  She said it likely was injected into the rotator cuff area from my description of where the bandage was located.  She measured 3 finger widths down from the boney point and injected into the muscle.  I did not have any worsening  mobility issues from the second dose.  I started physical therapy on 4/22/21 and go twice a week.  The physical therapist thinks I have an impingement.  Since beginning physical therapy, I have had some mobility improvement and pain is better but still not fully recovered.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The night of 2nd vaccine:  Extreme soreness and pain in left arm, from shoulder down to hand, to the point I could barely move arm; pain/soreness in right arm as well,  even though this was not the arm that received either of the shots; headache; chills the night of vaccine and then again about 30 hrs after vaccine; sweating(unsure if I had fever that night), but this afternoon I did check temperature and it was 100.4; entire body ached the night of vaccine and into the following day; brain fog (like I'd been drinking alcohol); swelling at injection site that is still present; swelling of fingers (I can tell because I couldn't get my ring off without forcing it).  This morning, Monday the 10th, awoke to  still a lot of brain fog and feeling exhausted   still swelling at injection site, but pain in the arm is almost gone. As of today at 1:30 p.m., found my abdomen (upper and lower) and entire back is covered in bright red (almost sunburn like) rash with a few small raised bumps here and there - the majority of the rash is smooth, but when you touch it it turns white like with a sunburn. I was in bed all day yesterday, Sunday, sleeping due to Extreme fatigue.

Delayed skin reaction - hives  I woke up the morning of Sunday (May 9 2021 - 14 days after 2nd Moderna shot) with a mostly full body hive reaction, concentrated especially on my thighs, but the hives reached all the way to the back and top of my head. Face was hive free. Hives are itchy but not unbearable if left alone. Treated with 2 benadryl (Diphenhydramine HCI, 25 mg), reaction went down. Later that same evening, hive reaction returned and worsened over the evening, this time the hives were concentrated on my forearms, especially on my right arm (injection site). The actual local injection site on the shoulder remained relatively hive free. Hives grew and joined together into large blotches. Treated with 3 benadryl. The next morning (May 10) I woke up my arms relatively hive free although there are some minor blotches. Now I have minor red blotches on my face and neck, and some on my lower legs. Treating with 1 benadryl. Will likely not seek medical attention unless hives worsen dramatically. No other symptoms - breathing is fine.   Unclear whether this is actually a reaction to the Moderna vaccine, but it is my best guess. There have been no changes to my diet, medications, or behavior. Bed sheets and clothing have been washed and changed without an effect on the reaction. I am not experiencing elevated stress. The concentration of the hives is moving around my body, so it doesn't appear to be the result of skin exposure or contact.

The patient developed headache approximately 2 weeks after receiving her vaccine and was found to have intraparenchymal hemorrhage (i.e. hemorrhagic stroke) and intraventricular hemorrhage in the setting of thrombocytopenia with a platelet count of 47 thousand. She was intubated and mechanically ventilated. Platelet count normalized 9 days after admission.  She underwent ventriculoperitoneal shunt placement 11 days after admission and was extubated 4 days later, then transferred out of the ICU 2 days after that.  Course complicated by pulmonary embolism diagnosed 4 days after she left the ICU which is being treated with apixiban.  She has a right hemiparesis and continues to have dysphagia and dysarthria.  She is dependent on NG feeds for nutrition.  Anticipate discharge to long-term acute care within the next 2-3 days.

Patient is a very pleasant 69-year-old Caucasian female who was recently diagnosed for acute CVA with right-sided weakness during admission at Medical Center on 1/13/2021, presents with a chief complaint of right-sided weakness and right-sided numbness.  Patient states that she was at Medical Center, admitted for acute CVA for 5 days.  She received a PT and OT and was getting better and thereafter discharged to home. Last night patient started having similar symptoms of weakness of the right side along with right-sided numbness.  Patient states that she started with tingling sensation on the bottom of the right foot.  This was new for the patient.  Patient tried to sleep and when she woke up she had right arm numbness.  She also felt weaker on the right upper and lower extremity.  Patient reported this to her husband and patient was subsequently brought to emergency department at Hospital.  Patient was noted to be hypertensive on the initial evaluation.  Patient reports her blood pressure was 158 over 80s last night and to her knowledge this was the highest blood pressure she had noted.  She had been told by her PCP to start amlodipine if her blood pressure went up.  She takes amlodipine 2.5 mg daily.  Patient also reported having more intense headache last night retro-orbitally.  Patient has on and off mild headaches.  Patient states that she had taken her first dose of cold vaccine last Sunday and was feeling generalized malaise for couple of days.  She recovered from this. Patient states she had been getting Evenity injection under the recommendation of osteoporosis specialist at Medical Center.  She had taken 8 out of 12 monthly injections and the last one was in middle of December 2020.  Patient had been warned by pharmacist at Medical Center in regard to the black box warning of this injection as it can predispose to MI and CVA.  Patient has stopped injection since the diagnosis of CVA at Medical Center.     Hospital Course: Patient was admission to hospital with concern for repeat stroke versus TIA.  She had a stroke January 13 diagnosed Medical Center.  She had gone to physical therapy and Occupational Therapy she is doing well.  She states yesterday he noted some numbness and tingling in her right foot which eventually spread up to her right leg she went to bed woke up in the morning with a heavy sensation in her right upper extremity and right leg and came to the hospital.  CTs in the emergency room demonstrated a small focal area of low-attenuation within the bilateral basal ganglia appearing a subacute to chronic infarcts.  She also underwent MRI which demonstrated subacute infarct involving the left corona radiata posterior left putamen with no associated hemorrhage. She was evaluated by neurology who recommended full-strength aspirin with Plavix for 21 days to follow-up with Medical Center.  She just underwent echocardiogram at Medical Center therefore this is not felt necessary to perform here.  I have placed an order for a cardiac event monitor to evaluate for any sign of dysrhythmia including atrial fibrillation or atrial flutter.  At time of discharge the patient's strength had returned she states that she felt like she did at the end of her rehabilitation.  She knows what exercises to do at home as well. SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had fever; fatigue; nausea; my joints were killing me in my spine. I was so tired, I couldn't walk from chair to the kitchen - about 10 feet. I started getting dizziness; and my right arm and my neck especially right side were really sore and stiff and hard to move. Along with the fatigue,  it was hard for me to talk or make sense - I couldn't concentrate or remember anything. It took me a few minutes to answer a basic question. I didn't eat much for a few days with the nausea. Fatigued for at least a week. The dizziness accompanied that. The fatigue and dizziness didn't go away. I started developing headaches where whole head was pounding and throbbing. I continued with headaches, fatigue and dizziness for almost the entire three weeks and even then some afterward. Saw Dr a few times. He hadn't really give me anything at all of any of the symptoms - told me it was a cytokine reaction from the latest research he had heard. He said the aches, fatigue and the headaches and the joint pain -Tylenol was the only thing that would work. I started taking Tylenol after that. The headaches and fatigue interfered with a lot of my life for two or three weeks.  I missed work for three weeks.

She got her vaccine, she had no symptoms at all.   The next day she had some body aches and fatigue, a headache that lasted for about a week.  Then on day #8 she started with a low grade fever that lasted for 8/9 days.  The highest temp was 101.3.  Most of the time went from 99.9 to 100.6.  Two of those days also had night sweats, headache for a few of those days, body aches and fatigue.  Then week #3 was mostly fatigue, a rash started on her buttocks and was covered, not itchy, but raised in nature that lasted for about #2 weeks.   Then she got a fever back again for a day.   On week 4 she got left lower quadrant pain that lasted for a week.  Then that was end of her symptoms.   She had a telehealth APT for her to return to work, this was during the low grade fever time.  She was then told to come in for blood work.  She had raised eosinophils which they were not concerned about.  They then sent her to hospital and gave her a COVID test, urinalysis, more blood work, chest x-ray.  She had two COVID and flu tests which were all negative.  The eosinophils were raised again during this visit.  She also had a positive Lyme test and then was told that she had either recovered from Lyme disease or that she was fighting something else.    She had a telehealth visit, two hospital visits and also sent for an ultrasound of her left lower quadrant which was negative.
ALLERGIES: Penicillin, Iodine, Erythromycin, Macrodantin.  Trees and things that grow on them, almonds, raw apples, plums, nectarines, peaches.

She states some of the symptoms started some time after his first dose but couldn't provide a time frame. On 5/6 he answered the Vaccine Questionnaire question of "are you sick today?" as "unsure" and further discussion was had with a pharmacist to verify he was eligible to receive vaccine. Neither the pharmacist or patient remember the details of this discussion.  Patient and wife have belief that his ethnicity contributed to dismissing of possible illness during the vaccine screening process, but due to the patient's lethargy and brain fog at the time, he could not provide specifics of the conversation. His wife was not with him during the screening process with the pharmacist or during vaccine administration. The appointment time was 4:55pm. The wife states the patient was so fatigued after the shot was administered on 5/6 that he was asleep in his chair in the observation area.  Later that day fever of 100.5 was noted and controlled by OTC ibuprofen 2 hours after the ibuprofen was administered. The wife states that he rapidly declined over the 3 days after second Pfizer vaccine and she called an ambulance on Sunday 5/9. From the ER he was admitted to the ICU with the primary reason for admission listed as hyperglycemia but a COVID was listed as a contributing factor. The COVID test administered Sunday was positive. He had high blood pressure, heart rate, blood sugar, and sodium. Patients vitals have since stabilized other than the sodium is still high. He is in ICU at hospital still very lethargic as of today 5/10.

As the day progressed (aroun noon) I confirmed a 99.3 fever.  No energy at all to get up only wanted to sleep bounced back in forth from being hot to being chilled.   Slight headache (about a 3 out of 10) some stiffness in my neck.  By 3:45 p.m. no interest in food, very tired, and fever hit 100.1. Took tylenol to help with symptons.  Slept off and on and ate what I could, and slept between eating and taking tylenol.  By 8:00 p.m. fever was gone.  Energy level was  still very low.  Slept as much as I could and continued eating small amounts often, hydrating with Gatorade.    Saturday morning felt like I had energy, but still had some stiffness in my neck and a slight headache (1 out of 10).  Took tylenol and returned to work.  Worked four hours came home ate and napped again.  Stiffness in neck would go away with Tylenol but return.  Woke up Sunday morning to only a slightly stiff neck, but that was gone by noon.  So as of noon Sunday all symptoms were gone.
