15 minutes status post 2nd dose vaccine, client complained of headache, nausea and dizziness. Medic made contact with client and noted she was CAOx4. Medic reported client tried to stand but was unsteady on her feet and was helped back into her chair. Client reported symptoms of nausea, headache (HA) and dizziness following her first dose Pfizer COVID vaccine received but said symptoms began late evening of 1st dose. This time she stated they began 15 minutes following 2nd dose. Client claimed last oral intake of food/water at 1100. Client remained in original seat for 15 minutes stating she felt more comfortable. Client was provided an emesis bag and water bottle. At 1145 baseline vital signs (VS) obtained while sitting: blood pressure (BP): 118/78, Heart rate (HR): 82, respiration rate (RR): 18, CAOx4, pupils equal, round and reactive to light (PEARL), and skins were pale, warm and dry. Client rated HA a 7/10 on pain scale and stated pain was in frontal/temporal region. Client positive for photophobia, nausea, dizziness and stated pain had a stinging sensation. Denied radiating pain, shortness of breath, chest pain, abdominal, neck  or back pain. Client denied recent trauma or illness, changes in lifestyle, diet, or prescriptions. Client was stable enough to transfer to zero gravity chair on her own accord. At 1200 second set of VS while sitting: BP: 118/70, HR: 69, RR: 16, CAOx4, PEARL, skins pink, warm, and dry. Client reported history of migraines and stated her prescription Sumatriptan would help. Client called a friend to bring her medication. Client was offered Emergency services (EMS) but declined. At 1207 orthostatic pressures attempted but unable to perform due to client stumbling back from dizziness. Medic caught client and assisted back to zero gravity chair. EMS offered again and client adamantly refused stating she will wait for medication. At 1210 Client reassessed and claimed no change in status. At 1247 Client's friend arrived with Sumatriptan. Client self administered 1 tablet. Client continued to complain of HA but stated nausea and dizziness subsiding. At 1300 client reported 5/10 HA and diminishing intensity. At 1307 client stood on own accord for orthostatic pressures which were negative, skins normal for ethnicity and dry, PEARL, negative for respiratory distress. Client reported 3/10 HA and denied other symptoms. Client departed at 1315 on her own accord with a steady gait.
PRIOR_VAX: Reported HA, nausea and dizziness in the evening of 04/16/2021 following  first dose Pfizer COVID vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I woke up the day after my first shot with severe eczema covering both hands, with particular intensity on the fingers. A few days after the shot, I also began developing a light full body rash, particularly on the sides of my torso. Eventually, after everything faded, I began getting some peeling skin on my fingers, which I assume were caused by the eczema.  I went to urgent care when this rash appeared. Here were her notes:  With patient having a recent diagnosis of strep, opted to order a group A strep test that was negative. Patient did not have any exudate noted in the OP. Patient's rash did start after having the COVID-19 vaccine. We will have patient continue to monitor for any increasing symptoms. If symptoms fail to improve or worsen over the next week, will have patient return to the urgent care or follow-up with his primary care provider for further evaluation and treatment. Patient may apply lubricating lotion over the areas. He stated that it was not itchy except for on the hands. He may apply calamine ointment or Benadryl cream to the areas of irritation.
LAB_DATA: The only test done was a rapid strep test to make sure I didn't still have it. It was negative. 4/19/2021

This is a 42-year-old female with an overall unremarkable past medical history seen in clinic for a hospital discharge follow-up.  She states that on 30  March she received first dose of her Covid vaccine.  Just over one week later she developed a red spotty rash across the left arm and left trunk that was itchy.  The rash has persisted until this time.  She has a history of plantar neuromas that have been surgically excised and has persistent left foot pain.  She felt a significant worsening of this so she went to the ER and was given prescription of Celebrex.  3 days after taking the Celebrex she developed symptoms of left-sided facial puffiness underneath the jaw and developed left-sided facial weakness and arm weakness.  Due to appropriate concern for a stroke she presented to the emergency room and was later admitted.  She had a number of CT scans and MRIs all of which were normal.  While she was in the hospital she underwent a number of blood tests which were ultimately negative.  She underwent an echo and after she sat up from having this completed she had a recurrence of the left-sided facial weakness. Neurology evaluated with the following comments, "42 yo female with no significant PMHx with onset of left facial weakness, left upper and lower extremity weakness and paresthesias. No lower extremity weakness on exam today and minimal give-way weakness in multiple muscle groups in the left upper extremity. No pronator drift. Reflexes are symmetric and intact. Sensory is intact in extremities. Left facial weakness is mild with some fluctuating features. No Bell?s phenomenon which is commonly seen with CN VII palsy. Imaging studies are not consistent with ischemic or hemorrhage stroke. Duration of symptoms are not consistent with TIA. MRI without evidence of demyelinating disease process. Low likelihood of migraine. Rash does not appear to be herpetic in nature. Other autoimmune processes are possible given the joint pain and tenderness. No significant edema on exam. Post vaccine response less likely. No ophthalmoplegia or ataxia. Consider facial dystonia."  Upon discharge from the hospital she has waxing and waning left-sided facial weakness.  She admits that it might be provoked the more that she talks or smiles.  Just prior to the patient's weakness episodes she will feel a pressure across the left temple around her ear.  She still has this pinpoint rash across left side of her abdomen and left arm.  There is a focal swelling in the antecubital space of her left arm that has never been characterized. Broad testing negative to this point. Potentially symptoms associated with moderna covid-19 vaccination. As outpatient she has been tested for myasthenia gravis, lyme disease, rheumatoid conditions. Empirically treated with prednisone long taper, acyclovir, and doxycycline all to no substantial benefit. At this time dedicated facial nerve MRI ordered and scheduled, and tertiary workup underway.
OTHER_MEDS: Celecoxib 100mg by mouth daily Pepcid OTC as needed GERD symptoms
HISTORY: Left Foot Morton's Neuroma - ongoing pain again since at least NOV2020 Left Foot Metatarsalgia Maxillary Sinusitis Urinary tract infection of bladder plantar fasciitis Mastodynia G2P3 (2nd was twins) Uterine myoma Left Calf Muscle Tear Left Wrist Ganglion Cyst Lobar Pneumonia IBS by history (not on treatment) hiatal hernia

Patient received a 0.5ML dose of Moderna Vaccine around 10:39AM.  She was asked to sit in the designated waiting area for the observed time of 15 minutes.  After 10 minutes a staff member went to check on her and the patient was complaining of some mild itching in the throat.  This was then brought the attention of the physician (myself) who came out to evaluate the patient's complaints.  Patient again complained about itching in the throat and mild difficulty in breathing.  Patient was then moved to an exam room, placed on a pulse device, and oxygen was administered.  Her pulse ox read 97-98 % on 3 L of 02.  Patient then became horse and had audible wheezing.  She reported having worsening difficulty in breathing.  Epinephrine was immediately administered, 0.3mg (mL) x 1 dose  in the left thigh.  Patient's symptoms improved within minutes.  Benadryl 50mg IM was also administered.  Vitals were taken at this point, her BP was 120/76 with pulse rate of 93 , respiratory rate of 16, and pulse ox of 98%.  Patient was continued on low dose oxygen and monitored for any progression of symptoms for an additional 25 minutes.  Patient was asked if she would like to be taken to the ER but she refused.  Patient was discharged home in stable condition.  Patient was contacted later on that day to assess for any changes in status and she reported that she had been perfectly fine since the initial intervention.

A couple of days later, I began itching in some places of my body, such as the elbows, underarms, and buttocks.  Soon hives accompanied the itching.  The hives and itching spread over most of my body.  I was prescribed antihistamines and took those for a month before it even started to get a little better.  Then, after another month, I was still itching all over, but the hives were not as bad.  On April 20th, the itching was still not much better, so I went to an allergist.  He prescribed that I take one 24 hour Allegra in the morning, and one at night.  In a week, the itching improved quite a bit.  Now I'm on 1 Allegra a day, and it seems under control. The allergist said that my immune system response to the vaccine may have played a role in triggering the chronic urticaria.
administered 0.5 mL of vaccine instead of 0.3 mL

Patient stated that she had never been diagnosed with Asthma. 1522 second set of V/S noted as BP 111/73, HR 69, O2 Sat 100%. At 1525 MD recommended Benadryl, and MD explained side effects of medication. Patient refused because she wanted to have the ability to drive. During the monitoring, patient disclosed already feeling anxious upon arrival to clinic. At 1531 MD told patient that he was observing that she was having more labored breathing, therefore patient was recommended to take the Benadryl and patient agreed. Patient was offered to call family member to pick her up, but patient declined and stated she would be okay to drive. 1550 V/S noted as following BP 113/72, HR 66, O2 Sat 100%, RR 20. Patient was asked to stand, Denied any dizziness or feeling sleepy. Patient left from clinic at 1554.
